This is the Requirement Policy you have to learn:
Software Requirements Policy (SRP)
Version 1.0

1. Format
1.1 Structure Description

1.1.1 Document Structure
1. Requirements are to be structured using XML files.
2. An XML file must either contain only High Level Requirements or only Low Level Requirements.
3. All documents must start with the <Requirements> tag.
4. The <Requirements> tag must have two attributes:
   a. “version”: the file's version
   b. “hierarchy”: specifies if the file contains only High Level Requirements (“HLR”) or only Low Level Requirements (“LLR”)

1.1.2 Requirement Structure
5. Below the <Requirements> tag, every requirement must be stored inside its own <Requirement> tag.
   a. The <Requirement> tag must contain “type”, denoting whether it is Functional Requirement (“FR”) or Non-Functional Requirement (“NFR”)

6. Each <Requirement> must contain the following child tags:
   a. <ID>: unique identifier for the requirement
   b. <Name>: name of the requirement
   c. <Content>: description of the requirement
   d. <Relationships>: contains relationships to other requirements

1.1.3 HLR Relationships
7. When defining a High Level Requirement, the <Relationships> tag can contain zero or more of the following:
   a. <DependsOn>: each containing the ID of a High-Level Requirement that this requirement depends on.

1.1.4 LLR Relationships
8. When defining a Low Level Requirement, the <Relationships> tag can contain zero or more of the following:
   a. <DependsOn>: each containing the ID of a Low-Level Requirement that this requirement depends on.
   b. <Refines>: each containing the ID of a High-Level Requirement this requirement refines.

1.2 Structure Template

1.2.1 High-Level Requirements
<Requirements version="{version}" hierarchy="HLR">
   <Requirement ID="{Requirement ID}">
       <Type>{Requirement Type}</Type>
       <Name>{Requirement Name}</Name>
       <Relationships>
           <DependsOn>{HLR this one depends on}</DependsOn>
       </Relationships>
       <Content>
           {Requirement Content}
       </Content>
   </Requirement>
   <!-- Repeat for each High Level Requirement -->
</Requirements>

1.2.2 Low-Level Requirements
<Requirements version="{version}" hierarchy="LLR">
   <Requirement ID="{Requirement ID}">
       <Type>{Requirement Type}</Type>
       <Name>{Requirement Name}</Name>
       <Relationships>
           <Refines>{HLR this one refines}</Refines>
           <DependsOn>{LLR this one depends on}</DependsOn>
       </Relationships>
       <Content>
           {Requirement Content}
       </Content>
   </Requirement>
   <!-- Repeat for each Low Level Requirement -->
</Requirements>

2. Traceability
2.1 Relationships

2.1.1 Refines
1. The Refines property is only applicable for Low-level requirements.
2. Only High-level requirements can be the target of the Refines relationship.
3. The Low-level requirement must not contradict the High-level requirements it refines.
4. Every part of any High-level requirement must be refined into a Low-level requirement.
5. Any part of any Low-level requirement must be traceable to a refined High-level requirement.

2.1.2 Depends On
1. The Depends On property is applicable for Low and High Level Requirements.
2. It describes a dependency between two requirements on the same or different layers
3. A requirements that refines another, cant point to it with the depends on property

3. Content
3.1 Hierarchy

3.1.1 High-Level Requirements
1. High-level requirements should be relatively broad in scope.
2. High-level requirements should describe the system capabilities.
3. High-level requirements must be testable.
4. High-level requirements must be implementable.
5. High-level requirements must be refined by at least one Low-level requirement.

3.1.2 Low-Level Requirements
6. Low-level requirements must always refine at least one High-level requirement, and can refine multiple if needed.
7. Low-level requirements should describe a specific system function.
8. Low-level requirements must be testable.
9. Low-level requirements must be implementable.

3.2 Identification
1. The content of the <ID> tag must conform to the pattern:
   “{level}-{category}-{section}.{item}”
   a. {level}: HL or LL
   b. {category}: category code (e.g., UI)
   c. {section}: major part of category
   d. {item}: sub-item (0 describes category)

2. The content of the <Name> tag must be a short description of the requirement.

3.3 Type
Type is noted in the type attribute of each requirement
3.3.1 Functional Requirements
Describe concrete functions of the system.
In the type attribute it is noted as "FR"

3.3.2 Non-Functional Requirements
Describe restrictions placed on the system.
In the type attribute it is noted as "NFR"

3.4 Wording
1. Requirements must be expressed in plain English using "shall".
2. Requirements must be understandable on their own.
3. Requirements must be unambiguous.
 

Make sure to ONLY answer with the output xml when requested


