  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Consistency of Cell Classification</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Once a cell is classified as BLOCKED, the system shall not reclassify it as FREE, and once a cell is classified as FREE, the system shall not reclassify it as BLOCKED unless marked as uncertain by a fault-tolerance mechanism handling sensor errors.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Map Origin and Start Cell</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall define the robot's initial position at the start of exploration as the origin of the maze coordinate system and shall store the corresponding grid cell index as the start cell.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Mapping Time Constraint Management</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall maintain an exploration timer starting at the beginning of exploration mode and shall ensure that the exploration termination logic is capable of stopping exploration such that the mapping process completes within 5 minutes of timer start under nominal conditions.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Time-Bounded Planning and Control Cycles</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall limit the execution time of exploration planning and control loop iterations so that the combined cycle time, including sensor processing, map update, path planning, and command output, does not exceed a configurable maximum period that supports completion of mapping within 5 minutes.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Path planning (HL-PLAN-3.1) -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Grid-Based Path Planning</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall compute paths as sequences of adjacent FREE cells in the maze grid, treating BLOCKED cells as non-traversable and UNKNOWN cells as non-traversable for planned optimal runs.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Optimality Criterion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall define path optimality in terms of minimum total path cost, where path cost is at least the sum of per-step costs proportional to the Euclidean or Manhattan distance between successive grid cells.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Shortest Path Algorithm</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a deterministic graph search algorithm, such as Dijkstra or A*, to compute the minimal-cost path on the grid from a start cell to a target cell using the defined path cost metric.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Replanning Capability</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support replanning of a path whenever the map is updated with new BLOCKED cells that intersect or invalidate the current planned path.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Representation for Controller</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall expose planned paths as ordered lists of waypoints in maze coordinates that can be consumed by the motion control subsystem to generate actuator commands.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Return to start and second run (HL-RUN-4.1, HL-RUN-4.2, HL-RUN-4.3) -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Return to Start Trigger</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      After exploration has terminated, the system shall automatically initiate a "Return to Start" phase without requiring additional user input.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Planning to Start Cell</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      During the "Return to Start" phase, the system shall compute a path from the robot's current cell to the stored start cell using the optimal path planning algorithm on the final map.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Return Path Execution</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall command the actuators to follow the planned path back to the start cell while continuing to obey collision avoidance constraints.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Mode Activation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      After the robot has returned to the start cell and is stationary, the system shall activate a "Second Run" mode that uses the stored maze map and planned optimal path to the target.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Start Condition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall start the second run either automatically after a configurable delay or upon reception of a dedicated start command from the user interface.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Most Efficient Path Selection</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Before executing the second run, the system shall compute the minimal-cost path from the start cell to the target cell on the final map using the defined optimality criterion and shall select this path for execution.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Path Execution</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      During the second run, the system shall command the robot to follow the selected optimal path with speed and acceleration parameters that may differ from exploration mode but still respect collision avoidance and actuator constraints.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Target Cell Definition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall define the target as a specific grid cell or set of cells identified during exploration, such as the goal cell detected by a goal marker, and shall store the target cell index for use in path planning.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Reliability and fault tolerance (HL-RELIAB-5.1, HL-RELIAB-5.2) -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.1.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Collision-Free State Invariant</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The control logic shall be designed such that any normal operating state with non-zero forward velocity implies that the predicted motion for at least one control cycle period does not intersect any region classified as a wall by the map or sensors.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Plausibility Check</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement plausibility checks on sensor data, such as range limits and rate-of-change thresholds, and shall mark any readings that violate these checks as invalid.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Graceful Degradation on Sensor Fault</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      When a sensor is detected as faulty or its data is marked invalid, the system shall either switch to a fallback sensor or exploration behavior with more conservative motion limits or shall enter a safe stop state while signalling the fault condition.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Redundant Wall Estimation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall, when multiple sensors observe the same maze region, combine their readings to determine wall presence using a rule such as majority voting or minimum distance to reduce the effect of faulty sensor data.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Interfaces: sensors and actuators (HL-INTERF-6.1, HL-INTERF-6.2) -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Acquisition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall periodically read raw data from each sensor specified in the sensor data interface description at or above its specified minimum sampling rate.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Conversion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall convert raw sensor data into standardized engineering units, such as centimeters for distance and degrees or radians for orientation, using calibration parameters defined in the sensor data interface description.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Timestamping of Sensor Readings</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall associate each sensor reading with a timestamp from a monotonic system clock to enable time-consistent fusion and processing.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Actuator Command Abstraction</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall represent actuator control commands using an abstract interface, such as desired linear and angular velocities or motor speed setpoints, that is mapped to the specific low-level motor command format defined in the motor interface description.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Actuator Command Rate</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall send actuator control commands to the motors at a fixed control rate, configurable but not less than 20 Hz during motion.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Motor Command Limits</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enforce configurable upper bounds on acceleration, deceleration, and maximum speed in the actuator commands so that motor commands remain within safe operating limits for the robot hardware.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Stop Command Interface</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide a dedicated command that immediately sets all drive motor speed references to zero and shall issue this command whenever an emergency stop or collision-imminent condition is detected.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>
</Requirements>

