  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Plausibility Check</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement plausibility checks on sensor data, such as range limits and rate-of-change thresholds, and shall mark any readings that violate these checks as invalid.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Graceful Degradation on Sensor Fault</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      When a sensor is detected as faulty or its data is marked invalid, the system shall select one of the following behaviors according to a predefined fault-handling policy: (a) if at least one alternative sensor covering the same field of view is available and operational, the system shall switch to using the fallback sensor while maintaining nominal motion limits; (b) if no alternative sensor is available but at least one forward-looking sensor remains operational, the system shall continue exploration with translational and rotational speed limits reduced to at most 50 percent of their nominal maximum values; or (c) if no required forward-looking sensors remain operational, the system shall enter a safe stop state and signal the fault condition.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Redundant Wall Estimation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall, when multiple sensors observe the same maze region, combine their readings to determine wall presence using a rule such as majority voting or minimum distance to reduce the effect of faulty sensor data.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

